{{hatnote|Not to be confused with his uncle of the same name but better known as [[Antioh Cantemir]].}}
[[File:Antioch Kantemir.jpg|thumb|250px|A portrait of Kantemir]]
'''Antiochus'''{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}} or '''Antioch{{sfnp|''EB''|1911}} Kantemir''' or '''Cantemir''' ({{lang-ru|Антиох Дмитриевич Кантемир}}, ''Antiokh Dmitrievich Kantemir''; {{lang-ro|Antioh Cantemir}}; {{lang-tr|Antioh Kantemiroğlu}}; {{lang-fr|Antioche Cantemir}}; 8 September 1708&nbsp;– 31 March 1744) was a [[Moldavia]]n who served as a [[Intellectual|man of letters]], [[diplomat]], and prince during the [[Russian Enlightenment]]. He has been called "the father of [[Russian poetry]]".

{{anchor|History|Biography}}

==Life==
Kantemir was born into a [[Cantemir dynasty|noble Moldavian family]] of [[Crimean Tatars|Crimean Tatar]] origin,{{sfnp|''EB''|1911}} "Kantemir" deriving from "[[Khan (surname)|Khan]] [[Timur]]",<ref>Anthony Kingsford, ''Companion to Russian Studies: Volume 2, An Introduction to Russian Language and Literature'', CUP Archive (1980), p. 114</ref> at [[Iaşi]] on 8 September 1708.{{sfnp|Gusterin|2008}} His illiterate grandfather [[Constantin Cantemir|Constantin]] had been made [[Voivode of Moldavia|voivode]] of [[Principality of Moldavia|Moldavia]] by the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottomans]] in 1685 and was succeeded by his well-educated sons [[Antioch Cantemir, Prince of Moldavia|Antioch]] and [[Demetrius Cantemir|Demetrius]]. Kantemir was the son of Demetrius by his wife, the Princess Kassandra [[Cantacuzino family|Cantacuzene]], who claimed descent from the [[Kantakouzenos|Byzantine dynasty]] of the same name.{{sfnp|Gusterin|2008}} He spent much of his youth in [[Constantinople]] as a hostage to the [[Ottoman Empire|Turks]].{{citation needed|date=June 2016}} He was then educated by his father and at the [[St&nbsp;Petersburg]] [[Saint Petersburg State University|Academy]]{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}} before moving to the family estate near [[Dmitrovsk]].{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}

He served as the Russian ambassador at [[London]] from 1731 to 1736, when he was relocated to [[Paris]] to serve as Russia's [[Diplomatic minister|minister plenipotentiary]] to the [[Kingdom of France]].{{sfnp|''EB''|1911}} There, he became a noted intellectual{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}} and a close friend of [[Montesquieu]] and [[Voltaire]]. Kantemir died a bachelor in [[Paris]] amid litigation concerning his illegitimate children.{{Citation needed|date=March 2007}}

==Work==
Considered "the father of [[Russian poetry]]",{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}} Kantemir used his [[Classicism|classical]] education to assist [[Peter the Great]]'s [[Russian Enlightenment|programme of modernizing and westernizing]] [[Russian culture]]. His most noticeable effort in this regard is his ''Petrida'', an unfinished [[epic poetry|epic]] glorifying the emperor. He produced a [[Tract (literature)|tract]] on old Russian [[Meter (poetry)|versification]] in 1744{{citation needed|date=June 2016}} and numerous [[ode]]s and [[fable]]s.{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}} His use of [[French poetry|gallic rhyme schemes]] can make his work seem antiquated and awkward to modern readers.{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}

He edited his father's ''History of the Growth and Decay of the Ottoman Empire'' in England and wrote a biography and bibliography of his father which later accompanied its 1756 edition.<ref>London: N. Tindal.</ref>{{sfnp|''EB''|1911}} His 1742 ''Letters on Nature and Man'' (''O Prirode i Cheloveke'') was a philosophical work.{{citation needed|date=June 2016}} He is best remembered for his [[satire]]s in the manner of [[Juvenal]], including ''To My Mind: On Those Who Blame Education'' and ''On the Envy and Pride of Evil-Minded Courtiers'', which were among the first such works in the Russian language.{{sfnp|''EB''|1911}}

Kantemir also translated [[Horace]] and [[Anacreon (poet)|Anacreon]] into Russian, as well as [[Algarotti]]'s ''[[Dialogues on Light and Colors]]''.{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}} His 1740 translation of [[Bernard le Bovier de Fontenelle|De Fontenelle]]'s ''[[Conversations on the Plurality of Worlds]]'' was partly censored as [[Heresy|heretical]].{{citation needed|date=June 2016}} His own works were translated into [[French language|French]] by the [[Abbé Guasco]], who also penned his biography.{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}}

