{{Orphan|date=March 2016}}
'''Harry McFarland Bracken''' (March 12, 1926<ref>http://www.public.asu.edu/~gelderen/Harry.htm</ref> – December 15, 2011<ref>http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/eastvalleytribune/obituary.aspx?pid=155136300</ref>) was an American philosopher, a specialist in [[René Descartes|Descartes]] and friend of Noam Chomsky. His academic career was framed in relation to his anti-Vietnam War activism.
Bracken received a BA in Philosophy from [[Trinity College (Connecticut)|Trinity College]] of Connecticut (1949), an MA in Philosophy from [[Johns Hopkins University|The Johns Hopkins University]] (1954), and a PhD in Philosophy from [[University of Iowa]] (1956). He held the position of Assistant Professor of Philosophy at the University of Iowa (1957–62); Associate Professor of philosophy at University of Minnesota, Minneapolis (1961-3) and then Arizona State University (1963-4) ;and finally Professor of philosophy at McGill University (1966–91). He was a Visiting Professor at Trinity College of Dublin; University of California, San Diego; National University of Ireland; Erasmus University of Rotterdam; and University of Groningen in the Netherlands.
== Bibliography == In addition to many articles and reviews, Bracken's published books are:
*''The Early Reception of Berkeley's Immaterialism: 1710-1733'', The Hague: Nijhoff, 1959;<ref>https://www.amazon.com/dp/940118674X</ref> revised ed., 1963. According to [[WorldCat]], the book is held in 484 libraries <ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/title/early-reception-of-berkeleys-immaterialism-1710-1733/oclc/489833354&referer=brief_results WorldCat book entry]</ref> *''Berkeley'', London: Macmillan, 1974<ref>https://www.amazon.com/dp/0312075952</ref> According to [[WorldCat]], the book is held in 597 libraries <ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/title/berkeley/oclc/780434717&referer=brief_results WorldCat book entry]</ref> *''Mind and Language: Essays on Descartes and Chomsky'', Dordrecht: FORIS, 1983 <ref>https://www.amazon.com/dp/9067650218</ref> *''Freedom of Speech: Words Are Not Deeds'', Westport CT: Praeger [Greenwood], 1994.<ref>https://www.amazon.com/dp/027594719X</ref> According to [[WorldCat]], the book is held in 648 libraries <ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/title/freedom-of-speech-words-are-not-deeds/oclc/715762495&referer=brief_results WorldCat book entry]</ref> *''Decartes''.<ref>https://www.amazon.com/dp/1851682945</ref> Oxford: Oneworld, 2002
