Once a peaceful stable location has been set, the yogi begins the posture exercises called ''asanas''. These Hatha yoga postures come in numerous forms. For a beginner yogi, states Mircea Eliade, these ''asanas'' are uncomfortable, typically difficult, cause the body shakes and typically unbearable to hold for extended periods of time.{{sfn|Mircea Eliade|2009|p=53}} However, with repetition and persistence, as the muscle tone improves, the effort reduces and posture improves. According to the Hatha yoga texts, each posture becomes perfect when the "effort disappears", one no longer thinks about the posture and one's body position, breathes normally per ''pranayama'', and is able to dwell in one's meditation (''anantasamapattibhyam'').{{sfn|Mircea Eliade|2009|pp=53-54, 66-70}}

The ''asanas'' discussed in different Hatha yoga texts vary significantly.{{sfn|Richard Rosen|2012|pp=78-88}} Unlike ancient yoga texts of Buddhism, Hinduism and Jainism, it is the Hatha yoga texts that provide step by step methodology on how to enter into an ''asana''. The Hindu text ''Gheranda samhita'', for example, in section 2.8 describes the ''padmasana'' for meditation.{{sfn|Mircea Eliade|2009|pp=53-54}} Most ''asanas'' are inspired by nature, such as a form of union with symmetric, harmonious flowing shapes of animals, birds or plants.{{sfn|Mircea Eliade|2009|pp=54-55}}

===Kundalini in later hatha yoga===
[[File:SahajaSubtleSystem.svg|thumb|Hatha yoga texts discuss sahaja and chakras.{{sfn|James Mallinson|2008|pp=231-237 notes 400, 433-434}}]]
{{main|Kundalini}}
Early hatha yoga was used to prevent the dripping of bindu (semen) from the heads of men.<ref name="JM" />{{rp|770}} The two early hatha yoga techniques were to stand on one's head (viparītakaranī) or make breath flow into the center channel which forces bindu up.<ref name="JM" />{{rp|770}}

However, in later hatha yoga, the [[Kaula (Hinduism)|Kaula]] visualization of Kuṇḍalini rising through a system of chakras is overlaid onto the earlier bindu-oriented system.<ref name="JM" />{{rp|770, 774}} The aim was to access amṛta (the nectar of immortality) situated in the head, which subsequently floods the body.<ref name="JM" />{{rp|770, 774}} This goal is in contradiction with the early hatha yoga goal of preserving bindu.<ref name="JM" />{{rp|770, 774}}

===Meditation===
The ''Hatha yoga pradipika'' text dedicates almost a third of its verses to meditation.{{sfn|Mikel Burley|2000|pp=6-7}} Similarly, other major texts of Hatha yoga such as ''Shiva samhita'' and ''Gheranda samhita'' discuss meditation.{{sfn|Guy L. Beck|1995|pp=102-103}} In all three texts, meditation is the ultimate goal of all the preparatory cleansing, asanas, pranayama and other steps. The aim of this meditation is to realize ''Nada-[[Brahman]]'', or the complete absorption and union with the Brahman through inner mystic sound.{{sfn|Guy L. Beck|1995|pp=102-103}} According to [[Guy Beck]] – a professor of Religious Studies known for his studies on Yoga and music, a Hatha yogi in this stage of practice seeks "inner union of physical opposites", into an inner state of [[samadhi]] that is described by Hatha yoga texts in terms of divine sounds, and as a union with ''Nada-Brahman'' in musical literature of ancient India.{{sfn|Guy L. Beck|1995|pp=107-110}}

===Goals===
The aims of Hatha yoga in various Indian traditions have been the same as those of other varieties of yoga. These include physical ''siddhis'' (special powers, bodily benefits such as slowing age effects, magical powers) and spiritual liberation ([[moksha]], mukti).{{sfn|James Mallinson|2011|p=770}}{{sfn|Mikel Burley|2000|pp=44-50, 99-100, 219-220}} According to Mikel Burley, some of the ''siddhis'' are symbolic references to the cherished soteriological goals of Indian religions. For example, the ''Vayu Siddhi'' or "conquest of the air" literally implies rising into the air as in levitation, but it likely has a symbolic meaning of "a state of consciousness into a vast ocean of space" or "voidness" ideas found respectively in Hinduism and Buddhism.{{sfn|Mikel Burley|2000|pp=203-204}}

Some traditions such as the [[Kaula (Hinduism)|Kaula]] tantric sect of Hinduism and Sahajiya tantric sect of Buddhism pursued more esoteric goals such as alchemy (Nagarjuna, Carpita), magic, ''kalavancana'' (cheating death) and ''parakayapravesa'' (entering another's body).{{sfn|James Mallinson|2011|p=770}}<ref>{{cite book|author=Paul E. Muller-Ortega|title=Triadic Heart of Siva, The: Kaula Tantricism of Abhinavagupta in the Non-dual Shaivism of Kashmir|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2maVlGOSdlMC&pg=PA55|date=31 March 2010|publisher=State University of New York Press|isbn=978-1-4384-1385-3|pages=55–56}}</ref>{{sfn|White|2011|pp=10–12}} James Mallinson, however, disagrees and suggests that such fringe practices are far removed from the mainstream Yoga's goal as meditation-driven means to liberation in Indian religions.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Mallinson | first=James | title=The Yogīs' Latest Trick | journal=Journal of the Royal Asiatic Society | publisher=Cambridge University Press (CUP) | volume=24 | issue=1 | year=2013 | pages=165–180 | doi=10.1017/s1356186313000734 }}</ref> The majority of historic Hatha yoga texts do not give any importance to ''siddhis''.{{sfn|James Mallinson|2011b|pp=329-330}} The mainstream practice considered the pursuit of magical powers as a distraction or hindrance to Hatha yoga's ultimate aim of spiritual liberation, self-knowledge or release from rebirth that the Indian traditions call ''mukti'' or ''[[moksha]]''.{{sfn|James Mallinson|2011|p=770}}{{sfn|Mikel Burley|2000|pp=44-50, 99-100, 219-220}}

The goals of Hatha yoga, in its earliest texts, were linked to ''mumukshu'' (seeker of liberation, moksha). The later texts added and experimented with the goals of ''bubhukshu'' (seeker of enjoyment, bhoga).{{sfn|James Mallinson|2011b|p=328}}

==Differences from Patanjali yoga==
Hatha yoga is a branch of yoga. It shares numerous ideas and doctrines with other forms of yoga, such as the more ancient Yoga system taught by [[Patanjali]]. The differences are in the addition of some aspects, and different emphasis on other aspects.{{sfn|Mikel Burley|2000|p=10}} For example, ''pranayama'' is crucial in all yogas, but it is the mainstay of Hatha yoga.{{sfn|Mark Singleton|2010|pp=29, 146-153}}{{sfn|Mikel Burley|2000|pp=10, 59-61, 99}} Mudras and certain kundalini-related ideas are included in Hatha yoga, but not mentioned in the Yoga Sutras of Patanjali.{{sfn|Mikel Burley|2000|pp=6-12, 60-61}} Patanjali yoga considers ''asanas'' important but dwells less on various ''asanas'' than the Hatha yoga texts. In contrast, the Hatha yoga texts consider meditation as important but dwell less on meditation methodology than Patanjali yoga.{{sfn|Mikel Burley|2000|pp=10, 59-63}}

The Hatha yoga texts acknowledge and refer to Patanjali yoga, attesting to the latter's antiquity. However, this acknowledgment is essentially only in passing, as they offer no serious commentary or exposition of Patanjali's system. This suggests that Hatha yoga developed as a branch of the more ancient yoga.{{sfn|Gerald James Larson|Ram Shankar Bhattacharya|Karl H. Potter|2008|pp=139-147}} According to P.V. Kane, Patanjali yoga concentrates more on the yoga of the mind, while Hatha yoga focuses on body and health.{{sfn|Gerald James Larson|Ram Shankar Bhattacharya|Karl H. Potter|2008|p=140}} Some Hindu texts do not recognize this distinction. For example, the ''[[Yogatattva Upanishad]]'' teaches a system that includes all aspects of the ''[[Yogasutras]]'' of Patanjali, and all additional elements of Hatha yoga practice.{{sfn|Gerald James Larson|Ram Shankar Bhattacharya|Karl H. Potter|2008|pp=140-141}}

==Impact==
{{see also|Yoga as exercise or alternative medicine}}
[[File:YogaClass.jpg|thumb|Students in a Hatha Yoga class practising the supta baddha konasana (reclining bound angle pose), sometimes called bound butterfly pose]]

The impact of Hatha yoga on physical and mental health has been a topic of systematic studies. Some scholars state that a regular and proper yoga practice yields health benefits.{{sfn |Mikel Burley |2000 |pp=227-230}}<ref>{{cite journal | last=Ross | first=Alyson | last2=Thomas | first2=Sue | title=The Health Benefits of Yoga and Exercise: A Review of Comparison Studies | journal=The Journal of Alternative and Complementary Medicine | volume=16 | issue=1 | year=2010 | pages=3–12 | doi=10.1089/acm.2009.0044 }}</ref><ref>[a] {{cite journal | author=Schell FJ, Allolio B, Schonecke OW | title=Physiological and psychological effects of Hatha-Yoga exercise in healthy women. | journal=Int J Psychosom | year= 1994 | volume= 41 | issue= 1-4 | pages= 46–52 | pmid=7843867 }}; [b] {{cite journal | last=Brisbon | first=Nicholas M. | last2=Lowery | first2=Glenn A. | title=Mindfulness and Levels of Stress: A Comparison of Beginner and Advanced Hatha Yoga Practitioners | journal=Journal of Religion and Health | publisher=Springer Nature | volume=50 | issue=4 | year=2009 | pages=931–941 | doi=10.1007/s10943-009-9305-3 }}</ref> Others state that the results of these studies have been mixed and inconclusive, with cancer studies suggesting none to unclear effectiveness, and others suggesting yoga may reduce risk factors and aid in a patient's psychological healing process.<ref>[a] {{cite journal |last=Smith |first=Kelly B. |first2=Caroline F. |last2=Pukall |title=An evidence-based review of yoga as a complementary intervention for patients with cancer |journal=Psycho-Oncology |date=May 2009 |volume=18 |issue=5 |pages=465–475 |doi=10.1002/pon.1411 |pmid=18821529}}; [b] {{cite journal |last=Sharma |first=Manoj |first2=Taj |last2= Haider |title=Yoga as an Alternative and Complementary Treatment for Asthma: A Systematic Review |journal=[[Journal of Evidence-Based Complementary & Alternative Medicine]] |date=October 2012 |volume=17 |issue=3 |pages=212–217 |doi=10.1177/2156587212453727}}; [c] {{cite journal |last=Innes |first=Kim E. |first2=Cheryl |last2=Bourguignon |title=Risk Indices Associated with the Insulin Resistance Syndrome, Cardiovascular Disease, and Possible Protection with Yoga: A Systematic Review |journal=[[Journal of the American Board of Family Medicine]] |date=November–December 2005 |volume=18 |issue=6 |pages=491–519 |doi=10.3122/jabfm.18.6.491}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1=Vancampfort | first1=D. | last2=Vansteeland | first2=K. | last3=Scheewe | first3=T. | last4=Probst | first4=M. | last5=Knapen | first5=J. | last6=De Herdt | first6=A. | last7=De Hert | first7=M. | title=Yoga in schizophrenia: a systematic review of randomised controlled trials | journal=[[Acta Psychiatrica Scandinavica]] |date=July 2012 | volume=126 | issue=1 | pages=12–20 | doi=10.1111/j.1600-0447.2012.01865.x}}</ref>

Yoga's combined focus on mindfulness, breathing, and physical movements bring health benefits with regular participation. Yoga participants report better sleep, increased energy levels and muscle tone, relief from muscle pain and stiffness, improved circulation and overall better general health. The breathing aspect of yoga can benefit heart rate and blood pressure.<ref>Jaloba, A. ''Nursing Standard''. 2011. Vol 25, Iss. 48, pp. 20–21.</ref>

The 2012 "Yoga in America" survey, conducted by Harris Interactive on behalf of ''[[Yoga Journal]]'', shows that the number of adult practitioners in the US is 20.4 million, or 8.7 percent. The survey reported that 44 percent of those not practicing yoga said they are interested in trying it.<ref>{{cite web |title=Yoga in America Study 2012 |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140331094110/https://www.yogajournal.com/press/yoga_in_america |publisher=Yoga Journal |accessdate=3 March 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140331094110/http://www.yogajournal.com/press/yoga_in_america |archivedate=31 March 2014 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>

